
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `laptop-detect` baraye inke motmaen shim shoma az laptop estefade mikonid ya na be kar mirevad. Age rooye laptop ejra beshe, yek paigham chap mikone.  

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 Heech gozine khas nadare. Tool sadeyeist.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ laptop-detect
    
    🔹 Agar rooye laptop ejra beshe, yek paigham chap mikone. Agar rooye desktop ejra beshe, hichi chap nemikone (yani output nadare).
    
    $ laptop-detect && echo "Shoma az laptop estefade mikonid."
    
    🔹 Agar `laptop-detect` ba movafaghiat ejra beshe (yani rooye laptop bashe), paigham "Shoma az laptop estefade mikonid." chap mishe.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ laptop-detect || echo "Shoma az desktop estefade mikonid."

    🔹 Agar `laptop-detect` ba movafaghiat ejra nashe (yani rooye desktop bashe), paigham "Shoma az desktop estefade mikonid." chap mishe.  Az `||` baraye ejraye dastoor dovom dar surati ke dastoor aval movafagh nashode estefade mikonim.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `laptop-detect` command is used to determine if the system is running on a laptop. If it detects a laptop, it prints a message.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 It doesn't have specific options. It's a straightforward tool.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ laptop-detect
    
    🔹 If run on a laptop, it prints a message to the terminal. If run on a desktop, it prints nothing (no output).

    $ laptop-detect && echo "You are using a laptop."
    
    🔹 If `laptop-detect` runs successfully (i.e., it's on a laptop), the message "You are using a laptop." is printed.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ laptop-detect || echo "You are using a desktop."

    🔹 If `laptop-detect` fails (i.e., it's on a desktop), the message "You are using a desktop." is printed. We use `||` to execute the second command only if the first command fails.

